==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|diurnālis}}, from {{m|la|diēs||day}}. Cognate with {{term|journal|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|[daɪˈɜː(ɹ).nəɫ]|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/daɪˈɝ.nəl/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-diurnal.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
*: {{rhymes|ɜː(r)nəl|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# Happening or [[occur]]ring during [[daylight]], or primarily [[active]] during that time.
#: ''Most birds are '''diurnal'''.''
#* Shakespeare
#*: Ere twice the horses of the sun shall bring / Their fiery torcher his '''diurnal''' ring.
# {{context|botany|lang=en}} Said of a flower [[open]], or releasing its [[perfume]] during daylight hours, but not at night.
# Having a daily [[cycle]] that is completed every 24 hours, usually referring to [[tasks]], [[processes]], [[tides]], or [[sunrise]] to [[sunset]].
# {{context|uncommon|lang=en}} Done [[once]] every day; [[daily]], [[quotidian]].
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} [[publish|Published]] daily.

